.SH NAME
Linux::Event::Signal \- signalfd adaptor for Linux::Event::Reactor
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&  use v5.36;
\&  use Linux::Event;
\&
\&  my $loop = Linux::Event\->new( model => \*(Aqreactor\*(Aq );
\&
\&  # Subscribe via the loop convenience method:
\&
\&  my $sub = $loop\->signal(\*(AqINT\*(Aq, sub ($loop, $sig, $count, $data) {
\&    $loop\->stop;
\&  });
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
\&\f(CW\*(C`Linux::Event::Signal\*(C'\fR adapts signalfd\-style signal delivery into the reactor
loop. Most users access it through \f(CW\*(C`$loop\->signal(...)\*(C'\fR rather than
constructing it directly.
.PP
Signal subscriptions are loop primitives. They are not a general\-purpose signal
framework.
.SH "CALLBACK ABI"
.IX Header "CALLBACK ABI"
Signal callbacks receive four arguments:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&  $cb\->($loop, $signal_name, $count, $data)
.Ve
.PP
\&\f(CW$count\fR is the number of queued deliveries drained in the current dispatch.
.SH SUBSCRIPTIONS
.IX Header "SUBSCRIPTIONS"
The returned subscription object supports \f(CW\*(C`cancel\*(C'\fR.
